{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653244"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18562"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18562"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.24,0.03,0.21,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114185"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11294"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96185"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"8487"},{"type":"tags","id":"10133"},{"type":"tags","id":"10506"},{"type":"tags","id":"10536"},{"type":"tags","id":"11278"},{"type":"tags","id":"11279"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114185"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe late distal tubule plays an important role in fine-tuning sodium reabsorption and maintaining electrolyte balance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes sodium reabsorption in the late distal tubule?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium reabsorption via sodium-glucose cotransporter","Sodium reabsorption via sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter","Sodium reabsorption via sodium-hydrogen exchanger","Sodium reabsorption via sodium-chloride cotransporter","Sodium reabsorption via epithelial sodium channels under aldosterone control"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the late distal tubule and collecting duct, \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium reabsorption via epithelial sodium channels under aldosterone control\u003C/strong\u003E is the predominant mechanism. Principal cells express epithelial sodium channels (ENaC) on their luminal membrane, which allow sodium to move from the tubular lumen into the cell down its electrochemical gradient. Aldosterone increases both the number and activity of these channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium reabsorption via sodium-chloride cotransporter\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the early distal tubule but not the late segment. \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium reabsorption via sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle. \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium reabsorption via sodium-glucose cotransporter\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the proximal tubule. \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium reabsorption via sodium-hydrogen exchanger\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily found in the proximal tubule. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium reabsorbed through ENaC channels is then transported out of the cell via the sodium-potassium ATPase on the basolateral membrane. This process creates a negative luminal potential that drives potassium secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The late distal tubule and collecting duct reabsorb sodium via epithelial sodium channels (ENaC) under aldosterone control.","Aldosterone increases sodium reabsorption by increasing ENaC expression and activity in the luminal membrane.","Principal cells are responsible for sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion in the late distal tubule."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 28; pg. 352.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96185"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96185"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T11:46:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:46:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11294"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114185"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0